TY  - JOUR
AU  - Bloom, Nicholas
AU  - Draca, Mirko
AU  - Van Reenen, John
T1  - Trade Induced Technical Change? The Impact of Chinese Imports on Innovation, IT and Productivity
PY  - 2016
Y1  - 2016/01/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdv039
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 83
IS  - 1
SP  - 87
EP  - 117
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  -  We examine the impact of Chinese import competition on broad measures of technical change—patenting, IT, and TFP—using new panel data across twelve European countries from 1996 to 2007. In particular, we establish that the absolute volume of innovation increases within the firms most affected by Chinese imports in their output markets. We correct for endogeneity using the removal of product-specific quotas following China's entry into the World Trade Organization in 2001. Chinese import competition led to increased technical change within firms and reallocated employment between firms towards more technologically advanced firms. These within and between effects were about equal in magnitude, and account for 14% of European technology upgrading over 2000–7 (and even more when we allow for offshoring to China). Rising Chinese import competition also led to falls in employment and the share of unskilled workers. In contrast to low-wage nations like China, developed countries had no significant effect on innovation. 
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdv039
ER  - 



